# Do not silently delete suspicious code

Never silently delete code paths that appear dead or wrong. If a path
looks buggy, add a `# TODO(bug):` comment describing the symptom and
suspected cause, and leave the behavior unchanged unless explicitly
asked to fix the bug.

The marker has three required parts: the literal `# TODO(bug):`
prefix, a one-line description of the **symptom** (what the user
observes when the bug fires), and a follow-up sentence on the
**suspected cause** (which invariant the code currently violates).
A future contributor must be able to grep `TODO(bug):` and triage
each hit without rereading the surrounding logic.

Two live `# TODO(bug):` markers are in the tree:

- the cross-fade cancellation gap in
  `frontend/src/hooks/useSvgCrossFade.js`'s `onAnimationEnd`
  callback (consumed by `MermaidDiagramSurface`'s outgoing-layer
  `onAnimationEnd` JSX prop). A user who flips OS-level
  reduced-motion during the ~200ms mermaid SVG cross-fade window
  sees the outgoing SVG layer stick on top of the incoming SVG
  until the next svg change for this block (typically the next
  theme toggle), because the global
  `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` rule in
  `frontend/src/index.css` overrides the keyframe `animation` to
  `none`, which fires `animationcancel` (not `animationend`) on
  the outgoing layer; React's `onAnimationEnd` JSX prop does not
  catch `animationcancel`, so `setOutgoingSvg(null)` is never
  called for the cancelled fade. Suspected fix is to attach an
  `animationcancel` listener via `addEventListener` in a
  `useEffect` (React JSX has no `onAnimationCancel` shorthand)
  with the same `setOutgoingSvg(null)` payload. Not regression-
  pinned because the frontend has no JS test harness, so the
  invariant would be enforced by the cross-referenced rule and
  by manual verification only.

- the cross-message mermaid singleton race in
  `frontend/src/components/chat-detail/ChatDetail.js`'s fetch
  effect, around the dual-theme `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` call
  pair. On a chat with multiple messages and many diagrams, some
  diagrams may render with the wrong theme on first paint (or
  after the first dark/light toggle from the cache), because the
  outer `Promise.all(rawMessages.map(...))` runs N message-level
  prerenders concurrently while each message's dual-theme pair
  fires `mermaid.initialize({ theme: ... })` with alternating
  values. Suspected cause: the in-message sequential `await` only
  serializes the two prerenders for ONE message; across messages
  the dual-theme pairs interleave, and once any message's B-pass
  calls `mermaid.initialize({ theme: !darkMode })` it overwrites
  the singleton baseline (mermaid's `processAndSetConfigs` calls
  `reset()` to that baseline at the start of every
  `mermaid.render`), so any other message's A-pass render that
  hasn't yet captured its config picks up the flipped theme and
  produces a wrong-themed SVG cached under `(source, darkMode)`.
  Suspected fix is to split into two sequential outer passes
  (one theme per pass), each using `Promise.all` over messages
  internally so all concurrent prerenders within a pass share
  one theme. Not regression-pinned because the frontend has no
  JS test harness; the invariant would be enforced by manual
  verification on a diagram-heavy multi-message chat (toggle
  through both themes and inspect each diagram's `stroke` /
  `fill` colors against the expected scheme).

